docs.abstract: George Floyd’s death continued to resonate far beyond Minneapolis, where he died. In Boston, Philadelphia, New York, Ferguson, Mo., Portland, Ore., Los Angeles and countless other cities, demonstrations raged.
docs.snippet: George Floyd’s death continued to resonate far beyond Minneapolis, where he died. In Boston, Philadelphia, New York, Ferguson, Mo., Portland, Ore., Los Angeles and countless other cities, demonstrations raged.
docs.lead_paragraph: For over two weeks, protests swept across the United States in a forceful outcry against systemic racism and police brutality inspired by the killing of George Floyd on May 25 in Minneapolis. A widely viewed video that showed Officer Derek Chauvin holding a knee to Mr. Floyd’s neck for nearly nine minutes provoked outrage and swift condemnation.

headline.main: In Photos: Protesters March in Cities Across America

docs.abstract: He expected to be the Brexit leader. Instead, he has presided uncomfortably over a public health crisis, an economic collapse and a racial reckoning.
docs.snippet: He expected to be the Brexit leader. Instead, he has presided uncomfortably over a public health crisis, an economic collapse and a racial reckoning.
docs.lead_paragraph: LONDON — After a week when protesters battled with police outside his residence, spray-painted “racist” on a memorial to Winston Churchill and dumped the statue of a 17th-century slave trader into Bristol harbor, Prime Minister Boris Johnson knew he was going to face questions about race and justice in Parliament.

headline.main: As Prime Minister, Boris Johnson Struggles to Find His Voice
headline.print_headline: Race, Health, Closings: Johnson Finds His Agenda Overrun by Events

docs.abstract: Smith, whose iconic protest alongside John Carlos at the 1968 Olympics shined a light on racial inequality, talked about today’s protests, Colin Kaepernick and what needs to happen now.
docs.snippet: Smith, whose iconic protest alongside John Carlos at the 1968 Olympics shined a light on racial inequality, talked about today’s protests, Colin Kaepernick and what needs to happen now.
docs.lead_paragraph: In 1968, Tommie Smith and John Carlos stepped to the podium at the Olympics in Mexico City to receive their medals in the 200-meter dash. Wearing black socks and no shoes to represent poverty and black gloves to signify black power and liberation, the sprinters raised their fists.

headline.main: Tommie Smith’s Fist Is Still Raised: ‘We Still Need to Fight’
headline.print_headline: Still Raising a Fist, 52 Years Later
